                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>1 Presde Ville Place</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>Nov 24 1847</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">My dear Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">You flatter me much when you say<lb/> you will be
                                        happy to count me among the few you favor with<lb/> an
                                        interchange of communication. Though I am pleased to stand
                                        in<lb/> correspondence with the <persName>Rev Isaac
                                                  Leeser</persName> Minister of the
                                                  <sic>Portugese</sic> Israelites<lb/> in
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> I am much more
                                        pleased to communicate with the Editor<lb/> of the Occident,
                                        and the author of the "Jewish Discourses," and of the
                                        "Mosaic<lb/> Law" If therefore I am at any time not to
                                        remedy in answering your favors<lb/> as this feeling would
                                        prompt, do not impute it to neglect but to its<lb/> true
                                        cause inability. It has been inability that has prevented my
                                        answering<lb/> yours of the <date>16th</date> till the
                                        present moment, and it has been inability that<lb/> has
                                        forbidden my sending you by opportunity of <persName>Mr
                                                  Joseph</persName> an article which<lb/> I have but
                                        just now been able to commence, and which I promised
                                        you<lb/> in my last. I know not whether it will suit the
                                        Occident, because<lb/> although a Jewish subject, it is
                                        likely to prove more interesting to the readers<lb/> of a
                                        British Periodical, it may be called an Essay or
                                                  <sic>Enquiry</sic> into the first<lb/> settlement
                                        of Jews in <placeName>England</placeName>. When in
                                                  <placeName>London</placeName> I took some little
                                        trouble<lb/> in collecting materials for the subject and in
                                        the above form they<lb/> are much at the service of yourself
                                        and of the readers of the Occident<lb/> Please let me know
                                        by earliest opportunity whether you [?] to<lb/> receive it.
                                        I would have sent you sermon for publication but<lb/>
                                        suppose that even now you would be unable to insert it
                                        from<lb/> the number you have on hand. Will my father's be
                                        among those<lb/> you intend publishing. English news would
                                        lead one to believe</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>that its remarks are as pertinent now as when delivered. News
                                        from<lb/> here I can send you but little, A friend who
                                        lately paid us a visit, and still<lb/> more lately visits
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> (I believe) is
                                        pleased to say "altho we Canadians do not<lb/> form (here)
                                        one of the largest and most influential congregations we
                                        prove that<lb/> we sufficiently understand what is [?] to
                                        the respectability of Synagogue worship<lb/> "The building
                                        is most striking for its very neat pretty appearance, marked
                                        decorum<lb/> pervaded the assembled, and an utter absence of
                                        that boisterousness, sometimes<lb/> unfortunately prevailing
                                        in our larger Synagogues was observable xxx The prayers<lb/>
                                        were read by the [Hebrew] <add>[?]</add> with an apparent
                                        desire to avoid that style which<lb/> reminds one so much of
                                        the opera and which for time and place is alike<lb/>
                                        objectionable xxxx It must be highly gratifying to you to
                                        know that your<lb/> discourses, and general services as
                                        reader and teacher are highly spoken of (dont[?]<lb/> you
                                        think dear friend I have some excuse if I grow vain?) My
                                        friend ([?]) continues,<lb/> But what pleased me most was to
                                        see your pupil (Mouther[?] I <persName>Ascher the son<lb/>
                                                  of the Parnass</persName>) called us
                                                  <persName>Maphlir[?]</persName>, The very correct
                                        and pleasing name of<lb/> his reading afforded me much
                                        pleasure." If you wish to give us all a fond<lb/> character
                                        here you can insert it in your news Items. The name of the
                                        writer (tho'<lb/> perhaps known to you shall be provided if
                                        you require it editorially tho'<lb/> I am not sure he would
                                        like it (his name) to appear in the Occident for All he says
                                        is–"If<lb/> you choose, write <persName>Mr Leeser</persName>
                                        what a <hi rend="underline">first rate</hi> character
                                        stranger gives<lb/> you." All the news I can give you of us
                                        (should you pronounce that <hi rend="underline">no</hi><lb/>
                                        news) is that our Parnas is <persName>Mr Ascher</persName>
                                        whose inde[?]able services as Parnas, and<lb/> whose jealous
                                        endeavors to promote the welfare and quiet of the
                                        community<lb/> with his <sic>colleage</sic>
                                        <persName>Dr David</persName>
                                        <del>the</del> President are mentioned by all in the
                                        highest<lb/> terms. They all have been unanimously
                                        re-elected. The formation[?] of the new Board of Trustees
                                        has <del>also</del> caused general satisfaction<lb/> among
                                                  <del>to</del> the members. These are
                                                  <persName>Messrs S. Benjamin</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Simon Hart</persName>, and
                                                  <persName>Jesse Joseph</persName>,<lb/> Treasurer
                                                  <persName>John Levy</persName> (re-elected) and
                                                  <persName>Levy Myer Solomons</persName> (also
                                        re-elected.) During<lb/> the late summer an unprecedented[?]
                                        number of German Jewish Emigrants visited<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Canada</placeName>, Indigent, and in many cases
                                        sick! They provide most services<lb/> drain on the funds of
                                        our Infant Philanthropic Society, About Thirty<lb/>
                                        unfortunate persons many with families besides one
                                        noatbly[?] pensioner, were<lb/> recipients. On [?] that the
                                        committee contemplated a Benefit Ball<lb/> but have not yet
                                        held any [?] of [?]. Should they determine<lb/> upon this,
                                        they will no doubt make it known in the Occident.<lb/> This
                                        dear friend is all the news I can scrape together
                                        concerning<lb/> our precious selves, and I have preferred
                                        giving you most of it as<lb/> an "Extract from a private
                                        communication" because if I had myself</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>undertaken to "give characters" I should altho' finding much to
                                        praise<lb/> still find a little to censure–But to other
                                        matters. I received last<lb/> week a letter from my friend
                                                  <persName>D Benisk</persName> now Editor of the
                                        Voice of Jews<lb/> He writes me that it is to be
                                        considerably enlarged and the whole to be<lb/> under his
                                        management. This last would imply, strange fingers in the
                                        Free<lb/> and I think this has been the case with the late
                                        [?] articles contend<lb/> in the Voice. In a letter received
                                        from my father the same mail he writes<lb/> "I hear that it
                                        is the intention of your friend <persName>Mr
                                                  Leeser</persName> to visit old<lb/>
                                        <placeName>England</placeName>–Do you know whether this is
                                        really the case, I should be most<lb/> happy to have it in
                                        my power to exercise my great esteem for him."<lb/> What am
                                        I to reply, dear friend? I hear this for the fist time.
                                        He<lb/> encloses me a prospectus of
                                                  <persName>Mayer's</persName> projected
                                        publication–What do<lb/> you think of this. There is no
                                        doubt I should say that as far as abilities,<lb/> Rabbinical
                                        and general knowledge so, there is not a man, christian or
                                        Jew<lb/> who is better able to answer <persName>Mr
                                                  C[?]</persName> than this said
                                                  <persName>Hoya</persName>. As a<lb/> Hebraist he
                                        has not I firmly believe his equal. Witness his
                                        [Hebrew]<lb/> and Hebrew Translation of <persName>Mr
                                                  Cauls</persName> Old Paths. Some attribute<lb/>
                                        the Heb version of the Christian Common Prayer to him but
                                        looking<lb/> at the style of that sublime composition I
                                        should doubt this much<lb/> His last articles too in the
                                                  <placeName>London</placeName> Jewish Chronicle
                                        are–to make<lb/> use of a mysterious old saying "not to be
                                        sneezed at. I am more<lb/> anxious to see his 1st no. The
                                        [?] of state [?] I suppose has<lb/> retired purposely to
                                        make room for the "faithful missionary" who<lb/> will
                                        doubtless occupy much room on the tables of the
                                        religious<lb/> reading world, but the Jewish Christian,
                                        altho' the same apathy<lb/> unfortunately exist to [?]
                                        [Hebrew] here, as on the subject of an<lb/> efficient
                                        ministry. With respect to this last the observation<lb/> of
                                        my father very often seems occurs to me. He very dryly
                                        observed one day<lb/> "The [Hebrew] to sail them must be
                                        [Hebrew] [?]"<lb/> and I think he is right. But I sincerely
                                        hope this unhealthy<lb/> state of things will give way to
                                        more worthy [?] notions<lb/> It has done so in many cases
                                        let us hope that its <sic>observence</sic><lb/> will soon be
                                        universal.</p>
                              <p>I informed <persName>Mrs Ascher</persName> of your invitation not
                                        to charge for<lb/> the nos, and she denies to acknowledge
                                        your politeness–</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>So you are a reformer. I have not yet seen your
                                                  <date>November</date> number<lb/> but doubt well
                                        that the reforms there propounded will shock<lb/> orthodox
                                        susceptibility but little, and that they are of a
                                        practiced<lb/> and [?]. I too am a reformer as far as
                                        endeavours<lb/> which I believe to be <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >consistent</hi> and legal, in improving the
                                        manner<lb/> of Synagogue worship are concerned. I don't
                                        think the cause of<lb/> orthodoxy would suffer much did
                                        conservative Synagogues introduce<lb/> quiet respectability
                                        in their services. Orthodoxy by nature<lb/> by age, and by
                                        character is respectable. Absurd and inconsistent<lb/>
                                        novelty in the Synagogue is disrefutable in its very
                                        essence<lb/> and it appears therefore a serious cruel
                                        anomaly that while<lb/> all that care [?] devotional
                                        feelings prevail in the new [?]<lb/> in the old, very much
                                        that is calculated to excite disgust<lb/> worldly and impure
                                        feelings is there observable. But my dear<lb/> friend
                                        [Hebrew], continue to sound in the unwilling ears<lb/> of
                                        the [Hebrew], and [?] success <hi rend="underline">must</hi>
                                        one day follow.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">"Prata albicaul camis friunis" Our Canadian
                                        winter<lb/> approaches in the shape of a few slight snow
                                        storms. See too<lb/> looks more plentiful in the streets
                                        than it did in summer, But<lb/> with all its severity
                                        speaking from last winters experienced<lb/> I like the
                                        winter here much. There is a [?] the cold [?]<lb/> clearness
                                        of atmosphere that renders the season here much more<lb/>
                                        agreeable and healthy than in
                                        <placeName>London</placeName>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I must now bid you good bye dear friend for<lb/>
                                        the present. Hoping you will write me very soon, and<lb/>
                                        [?] and that you may receive this [Hebrew]!</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">I am My dear Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">Yours very sincerely</p>
                              <p rend="indent(6)">
                                        <persName role="author">Abraham deSola</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p><persName>Mrs Joseph</persName> daughters desire</p>
                              <p>me to remember them to you</p>
                              <p>with comforts.</p>
                    </body>
